<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-728-579  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 728 579.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 10 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NCR bullish on Asian operation in 1991.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wingrove, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   NCR Corp. (Foreign operations).andO;Topic:     Pacific Rim CountriesForecastingAsia, EasternComputer industry.andO;Person:    Lee, Michael J.I. (Forecasts).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NCR BULLISH ON ASIAN OPERATION IN 1991  12/10/90 CENTRAL, HONG KONG, 1990 DEC10 (NB) -- NCR Asia-Pacific Managing Director, Michael J.I.andP;  Lee, has saidNCR business in the region is set to increase at about 20 percent in 1991,four times the company's projected growth worldwide.andM;Lee said the company's strong performance in the region comes primarily fromASEAN countries, and from China, where growth of 30 percent was recorded in1990.andM;&quot;China will continue to be one of the areas of greatest opportunity for us,&quot;Lee said.andP;  &quot;The eighth five-year plan will be unveiled shortly.andP;  This isexpected to contain major investments in telecommunications, which in turnwill create new opportunities both for direct sales of computer systems andfor joint ventures.&quot;andM;Lee said that in 1990, Asia contributed around three percent of NCR'sworldwide revenue, but around 10 percent of its profit.andP;  &quot;This is aconsiderable tribute to the productivity of our staff in the region,&quot; hesaid.andM;NCR's single best performing country during 1990 was the Philippines, wheregrowth exceeded 30 percent.andP;  Indonesia and Malaysia were also strongcontributors.andP;  &quot;In Hong Kong we saw growth, but not at the rate we had hopedfor,&quot; said Lee.andP;  Business was up by about 10 percent.andP;  In Hong Kong, thefinancial sector remains strong, but in the retail and commercial markets wehave experienced delays in the signing of major contracts, in part because ofthe general economic slowdown.&quot;andM;Lee said that NCR, like all computer vendors, would feel the impact for thenext two years of higher costs of doing business in Hong Kong, and by ageneral trend towards rationalization in the use of information systems.andM;&quot;Though the US government's decision to give an extra 36,000 entry visas toemployees of US companies here is a help, we anticipate that emigration willcause us problems for a few years more,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;[But] our focus on opensystems, industry standards and coexistence with other vendors will give us acompetitive edge at a time when overall sales may be thin on the ground.&quot;andM;(Norman Wingrove/19901207/Press Contact: Vivian Kung, NCR, + 852 859 6021; HKtime is GMT + 8)</TEXT></DOC>